WEBVTT

00:00:16.500 --> 00:00:19.700
Ladies and gentlemen,
please welcome Senior Director,

00:00:19.820 --> 00:00:22.800
Interactive Media Group,
Peter Graffagnino.

00:00:22.800 --> 00:00:24.780
Hi.

00:00:27.200 --> 00:00:28.960
Good afternoon, everybody.

00:00:29.080 --> 00:00:31.540
I know it's been a long day,
a lot of interesting and

00:00:31.540 --> 00:00:33.120
exciting announcements today.

00:00:33.120 --> 00:00:35.420
But this is the last session.

00:00:35.420 --> 00:00:38.380
I promise you it'll be worth
it that you stayed here for

00:00:38.440 --> 00:00:40.180
the last session of the day.

00:00:41.680 --> 00:00:42.780
So let's get started a little bit.

00:00:42.810 --> 00:00:47.750
We talked a lot about Leopard and
all the innovations this morning.

00:00:47.860 --> 00:00:51.190
But we in the system software
team have been busy on a few

00:00:51.190 --> 00:00:53.240
other projects this year as well.

00:00:53.660 --> 00:00:59.060
Both Apple TV and iPhone contain a lot
of the media and graphics technologies

00:00:59.430 --> 00:01:01.820
that we work on in Leopard as well.

00:01:02.520 --> 00:01:08.480
And so, if you look across Apple's entire
product line from Macs to iPhone,

00:01:08.680 --> 00:01:13.420
iPods, and Apple TV,
we really have a broad opportunity for

00:01:13.420 --> 00:01:16.930
you guys in a number of different areas.

00:01:16.960 --> 00:01:20.920
And I want everyone to kind of
think beyond just addressing

00:01:21.080 --> 00:01:24.540
the desktop and thinking about
some other platforms as well.

00:01:25.240 --> 00:01:28.000
So,
one way to kind of look at this universe

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:32.400
of evolving Apple products is to
think about kind of desktop platform,

00:01:32.400 --> 00:01:36.180
the web platform, and the media platform.

00:01:36.180 --> 00:01:38.680
And these are, you know,
not unique to Apple.

00:01:38.680 --> 00:01:40.900
Everyone out there is sort of
talking about these things.

00:01:40.920 --> 00:01:43.300
And a bunch of people think that,
you know,

00:01:43.300 --> 00:01:47.460
these are their forces at work and
these are all going to become one thing.

00:01:47.460 --> 00:01:50.860
It's going to be a grand universal
runtime to rule everything and it's

00:01:50.950 --> 00:01:55.000
going to play your media and do your
desktop computing and your web computing.

00:01:55.240 --> 00:01:57.790
And I guess my take on all that,
and maybe I'm just old,

00:01:57.790 --> 00:01:59.860
but I don't think that's going to happen.

00:01:59.920 --> 00:02:03.870
I have an analogy for this
just from thinking about,

00:02:04.050 --> 00:02:07.420
you know,
how we go about our daily lives.

00:02:07.600 --> 00:02:12.620
My desktop, at least my laptop,
I kind of feel is like my home.

00:02:12.620 --> 00:02:13.660
I mean, it's my stuff.

00:02:13.860 --> 00:02:17.560
The people I, you know,
people I let into my house,

00:02:17.670 --> 00:02:21.510
I know I kind of treat them a
little bit differently than someone

00:02:21.520 --> 00:02:23.160
I might just meet on the street.

00:02:23.280 --> 00:02:25.890
The web,
I kind of think like the... of the pub or

00:02:25.940 --> 00:02:28.440
the Village Green where it's very social.

00:02:28.550 --> 00:02:31.890
You go there, you may meet an old friend,
you may find a new friend,

00:02:31.890 --> 00:02:34.010
you may do a little
business with the bank.

00:02:34.020 --> 00:02:37.100
But you're kind of out
and social and connected.

00:02:37.120 --> 00:02:40.350
And it's a great platform for that, but,
you know, it's not where you live.

00:02:40.400 --> 00:02:43.610
Although I guess some
people live in the pub,

00:02:43.610 --> 00:02:43.900
but...

00:02:45.930 --> 00:02:47.560
Not everybody.

00:02:47.560 --> 00:02:51.340
The media is like a very different
kind of modality for people.

00:02:51.340 --> 00:02:54.440
You sit in a, you know,
in a movie theater and all the

00:02:54.980 --> 00:02:56.980
chairs face the same direction.

00:02:56.980 --> 00:03:00.910
You watch the screen,
it's kind of a very passive experience

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:04.340
where you're transported by a story.

00:03:04.360 --> 00:03:07.720
And so I think that these are, you know,
for all time have been

00:03:07.780 --> 00:03:12.320
kind of three different,
different ways we are.

00:03:12.320 --> 00:03:16.440
So I think that it's unclear to me that
these platforms are all gonna merge.

00:03:16.440 --> 00:03:21.160
It's also unclear for
some technical reasons.

00:03:21.400 --> 00:03:23.250
Let's look at the desktop.

00:03:23.300 --> 00:03:28.010
The desktop is really all about
performance and responsiveness.

00:03:28.010 --> 00:03:31.560
You have your hard disk
drive with lots of storage.

00:03:31.700 --> 00:03:34.160
You've got 64-bit computer.

00:03:34.260 --> 00:03:36.930
You've got all of the power of the GPU.

00:03:36.940 --> 00:03:40.790
You've got potentially
fiber channel connections.

00:03:40.790 --> 00:03:43.310
You've got multiple core CPUs.

00:03:43.500 --> 00:03:47.690
All of this power is really there
to drive the user experience and

00:03:47.710 --> 00:03:51.260
make the tool or the task that the
user is doing with the computer

00:03:51.330 --> 00:03:53.500
be performant and responsive.

00:03:53.500 --> 00:03:57.080
And so there's a big difference when
your data is kind of microseconds

00:03:57.080 --> 00:04:02.060
or milliseconds away than when it
might be minutes or hours away.

00:04:02.960 --> 00:04:03.900
Device connectivity.

00:04:03.900 --> 00:04:07.600
This is another thing where the
desktop is really essential for

00:04:07.600 --> 00:04:12.080
dealing with things like scanners,
printers, MIDI keyboards,

00:04:12.080 --> 00:04:13.730
cameras of all kinds.

00:04:13.730 --> 00:04:19.170
So again, you need rich frameworks to
be able to take this data in,

00:04:19.180 --> 00:04:22.000
use it, and put data out again.

00:04:22.740 --> 00:04:24.430
And trusted execution.

00:04:24.430 --> 00:04:29.660
The desktop is an environment where
it is your stuff on your hard drive,

00:04:29.680 --> 00:04:34.520
and the applications you run you trust
to help you to manage your life and to

00:04:34.520 --> 00:04:39.140
build your tools in your personal thing,
just like you might take

00:04:39.260 --> 00:04:41.680
care of things in your house.

00:04:42.920 --> 00:04:44.330
So let's talk about the web.

00:04:44.380 --> 00:04:48.670
The technical aspects of the web
that I think make it unique are,

00:04:48.710 --> 00:04:50.760
for one, its connectedness.

00:04:50.760 --> 00:04:54.440
I mean, it is a big cloud out there.

00:04:54.440 --> 00:04:56.920
Every site can connect
to every other site.

00:04:56.920 --> 00:04:57.850
It's very linked.

00:04:57.850 --> 00:04:58.960
It's interconnected.

00:04:59.090 --> 00:05:00.420
It's always on.

00:05:00.420 --> 00:05:04.500
Again,
it's like a social environment where

00:05:04.500 --> 00:05:07.810
people go to meet and communicate.

00:05:10.090 --> 00:05:12.610
The other important thing about the web,
and this is critical to the

00:05:12.710 --> 00:05:14.770
web in order to meet that
need of being a social place,

00:05:14.840 --> 00:05:16.780
is it's really platform independent.

00:05:16.780 --> 00:05:20.340
It doesn't matter if you're
running Windows or Mac or your

00:05:20.340 --> 00:05:22.340
iPhone or Linux or whatever.

00:05:22.340 --> 00:05:26.890
You can get on the web.

00:05:26.890 --> 00:05:26.890
You can take care of business.

00:05:26.890 --> 00:05:26.890
You can meet people.

00:05:27.560 --> 00:05:31.600
And also an important leg of
the whole ubiquity of the web

00:05:31.600 --> 00:05:33.770
is that it's based on standards.

00:05:33.870 --> 00:05:39.600
So you can have an implementation
that runs on a device or a

00:05:39.600 --> 00:05:43.090
desktop or multiple browsers.

00:05:43.110 --> 00:05:44.900
Content Media

00:05:46.590 --> 00:05:50.260
So this is a platform
that has the widest reach.

00:05:50.260 --> 00:05:53.860
There's a wide variety of devices
that can play back content and media,

00:05:53.860 --> 00:05:56.530
come in all form factors
and different trade-offs.

00:05:56.660 --> 00:06:03.990
Form factor, performance, battery life,
connectivity, and all of those things

00:06:04.070 --> 00:06:09.090
make it practically any form
factor device can play media.

00:06:10.490 --> 00:06:13.440
And media's really a
narrative experience.

00:06:13.480 --> 00:06:16.100
So it's usually a storytelling thing.

00:06:16.100 --> 00:06:20.960
You sit back, you get transported,
you go where the story's going to go.

00:06:20.960 --> 00:06:23.840
And you're in a different receptive mode.

00:06:23.840 --> 00:06:25.770
You're not participating.

00:06:25.840 --> 00:06:28.950
You're really being moved by the story.

00:06:28.960 --> 00:06:31.710
And lastly,
it's really limited interactivity.

00:06:31.840 --> 00:06:35.470
I mean, people tried to do interactive
storytelling with CD-ROMs

00:06:35.470 --> 00:06:38.970
and things like that,
and people didn't really want that.

00:06:38.980 --> 00:06:42.680
You really just want to take
where the director and the

00:06:42.770 --> 00:06:44.980
storyteller wanted you to go.

00:06:44.980 --> 00:06:48.920
So maybe you can time shift or play,
pause, stop, those kind of things,

00:06:49.230 --> 00:06:50.290
chapter navigation.

00:06:50.360 --> 00:06:53.260
But really, you turn it on,
and you just want to be entertained.

00:06:55.090 --> 00:06:57.620
So those are some of the
reasons why I think that,

00:06:57.620 --> 00:07:00.560
yeah,
we'll see a little blurring of the lines,

00:07:00.560 --> 00:07:04.660
but basically these three
platforms remain distinct.

00:07:04.690 --> 00:07:09.620
And obviously, they remain critical
to Apple on all fronts.

00:07:09.690 --> 00:07:17.450
So for example,
in the world of Apple devices,

00:07:17.450 --> 00:07:18.160
you could have a great
app on OS X on Leopard.

00:07:18.630 --> 00:07:24.130
Then you could develop a website,
which would be great on OS X,

00:07:24.290 --> 00:07:28.020
but that website would work
just fine on Windows as well,

00:07:28.420 --> 00:07:33.210
especially with WebKit on
Windows now and Safari on Windows.

00:07:33.500 --> 00:07:35.200
Or that website could work on your phone.

00:07:35.200 --> 00:07:40.170
You saw from Scott today how
great the phone is in being real

00:07:40.170 --> 00:07:43.190
high-fidelity web experience.

00:07:43.400 --> 00:07:55.400
( Transcript missing )

00:07:56.530 --> 00:08:02.060
So all of these platforms
form an ecosystem for content,

00:08:02.230 --> 00:08:06.270
for the web experiences,
and for desktop experiences.

00:08:06.430 --> 00:08:09.820
So in summary,
platform richness is really an

00:08:09.820 --> 00:08:13.120
area where the desktop wins because
it's closest to the hardware.

00:08:13.170 --> 00:08:15.780
The web is pretty rich,
and Darren's going to have some

00:08:15.790 --> 00:08:18.080
great demos later of web experiences.

00:08:18.260 --> 00:08:22.780
And of course,
media is everywhere but not as rich.

00:08:22.860 --> 00:08:25.780
Platform connectedness is
really where the web excels.

00:08:25.840 --> 00:08:29.090
Desktop is pretty connected as well,
but there's not as much of agreement

00:08:29.090 --> 00:08:33.900
on the protocols that people use for
file sharing and things like that.

00:08:34.270 --> 00:08:46.890
Media is typically not
a connected experience.

00:08:46.890 --> 00:08:46.890
People are playing with this area,
but frankly,

00:08:46.890 --> 00:08:46.890
I'm not sure that's what I want
to do when I'm being entertained.

00:08:47.120 --> 00:08:52.470
Now, if you really want to talk about
hitting that broad variety of devices,

00:08:52.720 --> 00:08:57.140
whether it's DVD players or your
home theater system or an iPod,

00:08:57.140 --> 00:08:59.860
then media is really everywhere.

00:08:59.860 --> 00:09:04.310
And so that's where media really
has an advantage in terms of reach.

00:09:04.860 --> 00:09:08.200
So those three platforms are
the way I set up the talk today

00:09:08.200 --> 00:09:11.880
to talk about the desktop,
we're going to talk about the web,

00:09:11.880 --> 00:09:14.850
and we're going to talk about
the media and kind of how all of

00:09:14.850 --> 00:09:18.560
these things create opportunity
for you and your applications.

00:09:18.560 --> 00:09:20.780
First up is going to be the desktop.

00:09:20.780 --> 00:09:23.690
We're going to talk about
Mac OS X Leopard and all the graphics and

00:09:23.790 --> 00:09:25.810
media technologies we have for you there.

00:09:25.810 --> 00:09:28.660
And to do that,
I'd like to invite John Stauffer

00:09:28.660 --> 00:09:33.170
up to the stage to take you through
making great desktop applications.

00:09:38.600 --> 00:09:42.000
Thank you, Peter, and welcome.

00:09:42.070 --> 00:09:47.300
So today, I'm going to be talking about
making great desktop applications.

00:09:48.180 --> 00:09:50.960
And more specifically,
I'm going to be talking about

00:09:50.960 --> 00:09:54.730
something more dear to my heart,
which is making great desktop

00:09:54.750 --> 00:09:59.360
applications using graphics and
media technologies inside of Leopard.

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:01.820
So let's get started.

00:10:01.820 --> 00:10:03.740
So the technologies that
I wanted to highlight,

00:10:03.740 --> 00:10:06.360
that I wanted to encourage
you to learn more about,

00:10:06.460 --> 00:10:11.030
that we wanted to have you look
at in integrating into your

00:10:11.110 --> 00:10:17.580
applications is Core Animation,
ImageKit, Core Image, OpenGL,

00:10:17.660 --> 00:10:19.080
and QuickTime.

00:10:19.100 --> 00:10:21.590
These are the technologies
that we're going to talk about.

00:10:21.810 --> 00:10:24.880
We're going to run through some demos.

00:10:24.880 --> 00:10:27.000
We're going to look at some examples.

00:10:27.030 --> 00:10:32.050
And what's important to understand as
we walk through and we talk about these

00:10:32.050 --> 00:10:36.600
is that these technologies not only
are for enhancing your application,

00:10:36.670 --> 00:10:39.040
for enhancing the user
experience of your application,

00:10:39.070 --> 00:10:42.360
but they can perform the heavy
lifting of your application.

00:10:42.380 --> 00:10:47.060
They can do a lot of the work that
your application needs to get done.

00:10:49.590 --> 00:10:52.590
So to start with, I'm going to read a
quote from a developer,

00:10:52.600 --> 00:10:55.660
Will Shipley of Delicious Monster.

00:10:55.660 --> 00:10:58.800
And Will has had the chance to use
Core Animation since we seeded it,

00:10:58.870 --> 00:11:00.170
and here's what he has to say about it.

00:11:00.260 --> 00:11:04.400
"The revolution coming from
Core Animation is akin to the one that

00:11:04.400 --> 00:11:06.410
came from the original Mac in 1984.

00:11:06.530 --> 00:11:09.290
We're going to see a whole
new world of user interface

00:11:09.340 --> 00:11:13.180
metaphors with Core Animation."

00:11:14.980 --> 00:11:20.170
summarizes how we feel about it,
and that is that it brings -- it

00:11:20.340 --> 00:11:25.470
enables you as the application
developer to rethink and refactor

00:11:25.470 --> 00:11:31.790
your applications to build new
capabilities into your application.

00:11:35.220 --> 00:11:36.980
So let's talk about it a little bit.

00:11:37.080 --> 00:11:41.030
So at Apple,
we've been doing exactly that.

00:11:41.110 --> 00:11:47.130
We've been rethinking our applications,
our user interfaces, and--

00:11:48.070 --> 00:11:50.460
We wanted to bring
that capability to you.

00:11:50.460 --> 00:11:54.000
We wanted to expose it in a
way that you could do the same.

00:11:54.080 --> 00:11:55.900
And that's why we built Core Animation.

00:11:56.010 --> 00:12:00.680
We built it for you to do the same
kinds of things we're doing at Apple.

00:12:00.780 --> 00:12:03.830
So Core Animation is a
layer-based framework.

00:12:03.830 --> 00:12:09.300
And what that means is that it's -- a
layer is 2D planes arranged in 3D space.

00:12:09.300 --> 00:12:13.990
And Core Animation handles
the animation of those planes

00:12:16.140 --> 00:12:19.840
So Core Automation comes with
a very easy programming model.

00:12:19.890 --> 00:12:23.350
It makes it easy for you to leverage it.

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:29.020
Core animation supports
transparencies in these layers,

00:12:29.020 --> 00:12:32.730
and it supports all the filter
effects that come with Mac OS X,

00:12:32.860 --> 00:12:36.580
all the filter effects that
are part of core image.

00:12:36.910 --> 00:12:39.260
It supports multiple media
types in these layers,

00:12:39.270 --> 00:12:42.620
such as text, 2D graphics,

00:12:42.870 --> 00:12:45.680
OpenGL can be embedded
on a layer and animated,

00:12:45.680 --> 00:12:48.300
and the same can be done with QuickTime.

00:12:48.470 --> 00:12:53.770
So a layer is a fairly
expressive type of media.

00:12:54.540 --> 00:12:57.580
And Core Animation is
GPU-accelerated and multithreaded,

00:12:57.580 --> 00:13:02.090
so it gives you the performance you need
to handle the most demanding animations.

00:13:02.150 --> 00:13:05.210
It's a very powerful API.

00:13:05.470 --> 00:13:11.640
So Core Animation is built to deliver
high production value experiences.

00:13:11.670 --> 00:13:13.590
That's what we built it for.

00:13:16.470 --> 00:13:20.800
So Time Machine is a great
example of using Core Animation.

00:13:20.830 --> 00:13:26.280
Time Machine takes what normally would
be a mundane task of backing up files

00:13:26.280 --> 00:13:29.390
and makes it into an interesting,

00:13:29.760 --> 00:13:32.900
and usable application for a user.

00:13:32.920 --> 00:13:35.410
It takes the content,
it takes the function of that

00:13:35.410 --> 00:13:37.130
application and makes it foremost.

00:13:37.250 --> 00:13:40.400
It makes it the thing that everyone,
that the user is focused on.

00:13:40.420 --> 00:13:42.440
It makes it clear to use.

00:13:42.560 --> 00:13:48.540
So it's a good example of
the type of rethinking,

00:13:48.540 --> 00:13:48.540
refactoring you can do
with an application.

00:13:49.740 --> 00:13:55.600
So let's do a demo of Core Animation,
and let's show some examples of

00:13:55.600 --> 00:13:58.460
diving into it a little bit more.

00:14:04.030 --> 00:14:09.400
So many of you have seen
this demo in the keynote.

00:14:09.400 --> 00:14:11.980
But what I want to do is I want
to talk about the mechanics

00:14:11.980 --> 00:14:13.430
behind it a little bit.

00:14:14.410 --> 00:14:17.290
So we talked about layers and space.

00:14:17.450 --> 00:14:22.170
So as you can see,
these are just layers arranged in space.

00:14:23.080 --> 00:14:27.240
And the power of core
animation is in its animation,

00:14:27.320 --> 00:14:27.730
right?

00:14:27.820 --> 00:14:33.290
So as I type a search key,
I see that these layers are animating.

00:14:33.390 --> 00:14:37.090
And what's important to understand
here is that LayerKit is

00:14:37.090 --> 00:14:40.470
handling that animation for you.

00:14:40.820 --> 00:14:44.360
The application is defining
the beginning and the end

00:14:44.410 --> 00:14:46.460
state of those layers in space.

00:14:46.530 --> 00:14:49.580
And Core Animation is
moving them there for you.

00:14:49.580 --> 00:14:52.530
It's animating those layers in space.

00:14:53.920 --> 00:14:56.140
That is all just part
of Core Animation and

00:14:56.140 --> 00:14:57.800
free with Core Animation.

00:14:57.850 --> 00:15:00.890
So we also talked a little bit
about different media types

00:15:00.970 --> 00:15:02.680
that can be put onto a layer.

00:15:02.740 --> 00:15:06.040
Let's look at that a little bit closer.

00:15:06.170 --> 00:15:10.700
So we see video here,
but we talked about still images.

00:15:10.850 --> 00:15:15.430
So it can handle still images.

00:15:15.430 --> 00:15:15.430
It can handle text.

00:15:15.690 --> 00:15:18.310
But what's interesting here is
there's another layer behind this.

00:15:18.340 --> 00:15:21.560
There's another nugget
of functionality here.

00:15:21.680 --> 00:15:27.310
And that is that Core Automation
can handle levels of detail as well.

00:15:27.600 --> 00:15:32.320
So I can sit here and zoom into
this PDF that has text on it.

00:15:32.650 --> 00:15:36.910
And what happens is Core Animation calls
back to the application and

00:15:37.040 --> 00:15:38.890
asks it to redraw this text.

00:15:39.690 --> 00:15:40.590
at full resolution.

00:15:40.600 --> 00:15:43.200
So as I zoom in,
I'm getting full-quality text,

00:15:43.200 --> 00:15:45.810
even though I'm zooming in on a document.

00:15:45.810 --> 00:15:49.070
And I can zoom back out,
and Core Animation, again,

00:15:49.090 --> 00:15:51.370
is handling the level of detail.

00:15:52.580 --> 00:15:54.380
So, you know,
the same thing can be done with

00:15:54.460 --> 00:15:57.910
other types of PDFs or rendering.

00:15:58.050 --> 00:15:59.830
You know, so here's a map.

00:15:59.890 --> 00:16:00.900
I can zoom in on this.

00:16:00.900 --> 00:16:04.060
And again, you can see I'm getting
full-quality rendering.

00:16:04.060 --> 00:16:12.400
So let's go back to slides.

00:16:19.990 --> 00:16:22.940
So that's Core Animation.

00:16:23.000 --> 00:16:26.930
So at Apple, we've also been building

00:16:27.600 --> 00:16:31.840
robust image viewing and
thumbnail viewing capabilities

00:16:31.840 --> 00:16:35.440
into our applications and
into the operating system.

00:16:35.440 --> 00:16:39.080
And this also led us to build ImageKit.

00:16:39.080 --> 00:16:39.080
ImageKit,

00:16:39.590 --> 00:16:43.580
is built for you to be able to do
that same thing in your products,

00:16:43.630 --> 00:16:45.250
your applications.

00:16:45.870 --> 00:16:53.910
So ImageKit is a Cocoa framework that
handles your common image handling tasks.

00:16:53.920 --> 00:16:56.260
It has a robust image
view for viewing images,

00:16:56.260 --> 00:16:58.140
but it's not just for viewing them.

00:16:58.140 --> 00:17:01.800
It handles common editing
tasks like rotate,

00:17:01.800 --> 00:17:05.140
crop, scale,
and it can also apply all the

00:17:05.140 --> 00:17:07.020
filter effects of core image.

00:17:07.020 --> 00:17:10.780
So you can take the image and
you can perform a whole wealth

00:17:10.780 --> 00:17:15.340
of operations and filtering
tasks on that image in the view.

00:17:16.800 --> 00:17:20.210
It also comes with a
high-performance browser,

00:17:20.210 --> 00:17:22.640
thumbnail browser,
and we've spent the time to

00:17:22.700 --> 00:17:26.580
optimize this such that it can
handle a large number of images.

00:17:26.580 --> 00:17:34.290
In fact,
it can handle up to 250,000 images,

00:17:34.290 --> 00:17:34.290
so that no matter what
your user is doing,

00:17:34.290 --> 00:17:34.290
if they happen to

00:17:34.510 --> 00:17:38.160
If you pick their iPhoto
library on their file system,

00:17:38.210 --> 00:17:40.750
your application won't all
of a sudden come to a stop.

00:17:40.820 --> 00:17:44.250
It'll actually handle it
robustly and manage that.

00:17:45.100 --> 00:17:49.530
It comes with a slideshow and
a picture taker for giving your

00:17:49.530 --> 00:17:53.780
users full-screen picture viewing
and integration with the camera.

00:17:53.890 --> 00:17:55.100
And it leverages Core Animation.

00:17:55.120 --> 00:17:59.920
So this is a technology that
layers on top of Core Animation for

00:17:59.920 --> 00:18:02.240
some of its functionality.

00:18:02.360 --> 00:18:05.410
So let's go back and let's
look at a demo of that.

00:18:11.560 --> 00:18:15.510
So here we see a fairly
basic application.

00:18:15.910 --> 00:18:19.030
On the top, where the fish are,
that is the image view.

00:18:19.070 --> 00:18:22.510
The bottom section of the screen,
where the thumbnails,

00:18:22.510 --> 00:18:24.290
that is the image browser.

00:18:24.520 --> 00:18:28.790
So as I said, you can perform basic
operations like rotates.

00:18:28.850 --> 00:18:31.180
You can perform scales.

00:18:32.230 --> 00:18:35.340
And that's all just built in.

00:18:35.440 --> 00:18:39.900
At the bottom here,
we have the thumbnail browser.

00:18:40.250 --> 00:18:42.910
And you can see that it
gives you smooth scrolling,

00:18:42.910 --> 00:18:45.540
but it handles other
types of tasks as well.

00:18:45.540 --> 00:18:49.180
For instance,
if I select some images and I move them,

00:18:49.210 --> 00:18:59.070
the image browser automatically handles
the animation and the reordering,

00:18:59.070 --> 00:18:59.070
so it gives you a smooth,
polished look of

00:18:59.070 --> 00:18:59.070
managing your thumbnails.

00:18:59.570 --> 00:19:01.500
So right now I have 46 images in here.

00:19:01.500 --> 00:19:05.570
Let's throw another 5,000 in there.

00:19:06.190 --> 00:19:07.960
Just drag it and drop it in there.

00:19:08.010 --> 00:19:09.670
You can see very quickly
it imported those.

00:19:09.740 --> 00:19:12.540
They're very responsive.

00:19:12.580 --> 00:19:15.140
And again,
I can sit here and just scroll these.

00:19:15.180 --> 00:19:22.290
And as I scroll quickly
through these thumbnails,

00:19:22.300 --> 00:19:22.990
ImageKit is off building
the thumbnails for me,

00:19:22.990 --> 00:19:22.990
building the thumbnails
and displaying them.

00:19:23.460 --> 00:19:27.410
But what it can also do is,
let's say I scale these thumbnails.

00:19:27.520 --> 00:19:32.050
Core animation, I'm sorry,
ImageKit is off building the

00:19:32.140 --> 00:19:35.440
thumbnails at the new resolution.

00:19:35.540 --> 00:19:41.900
So it's all very easy for you
to have this kind of capability

00:19:41.900 --> 00:19:45.760
built into your application.

00:19:45.770 --> 00:19:47.970
OK, let's go back to slides.

00:20:01.710 --> 00:20:02.230
Core Image.

00:20:02.350 --> 00:20:06.100
So Core Image is not new for Leopard,
but it's a technology that we

00:20:06.100 --> 00:20:08.560
have continued to invest in.

00:20:08.590 --> 00:20:12.060
It's a technology that we
feel is a key technology,

00:20:12.060 --> 00:20:19.130
and it is the backbone of image
processing inside the operating system.

00:20:19.700 --> 00:20:27.900
( Transcript missing )

00:20:28.190 --> 00:20:31.520
We've made it extensible through
custom image units so you can

00:20:31.520 --> 00:20:35.900
write your own effects and extend
the capability of core image.

00:20:36.040 --> 00:20:39.060
And it's based on a full
floating point implementation,

00:20:39.060 --> 00:20:43.650
meaning that you get professional-grade
image processing in your application.

00:20:44.510 --> 00:20:48.070
Like our other technologies,
we spent the time to GPU accelerate

00:20:48.070 --> 00:20:51.430
and multi-thread core image.

00:20:51.850 --> 00:20:55.720
And Core Image, like I mentioned before,
it is used by some of

00:20:55.720 --> 00:20:59.100
our other technologies,
like Core Animation and ImageKit.

00:20:59.250 --> 00:21:05.240
It is the filter effects
technology in those APIs.

00:21:05.320 --> 00:21:08.660
So new for Leopard,
we've added 25 new effects.

00:21:08.720 --> 00:21:12.590
We've added 64-bit support for
handling those large images.

00:21:12.690 --> 00:21:13.900
And we've enhanced performance.

00:21:14.080 --> 00:21:17.140
In some cases, we've enhanced performance
by as much as 10x.

00:21:17.140 --> 00:21:19.880
So we've been investing
and improving this,

00:21:19.890 --> 00:21:22.680
and it's going to be a great
technology for Leopard.

00:21:27.530 --> 00:21:29.300
OpenGL.

00:21:29.350 --> 00:21:33.530
So OpenGL, we look at it as the bedrock
of graphics on Mac OS X.

00:21:33.590 --> 00:21:40.690
It is the harder abstraction
layer at which you access the GPU.

00:21:40.820 --> 00:21:43.490
It is that lowest level API.

00:21:44.190 --> 00:21:47.340
Many of the technologies that
we've been talking about,

00:21:47.340 --> 00:21:51.480
and many others, directly or indirectly,
leverage OpenGL to accelerate

00:21:52.190 --> 00:21:54.120
through the graphics processor.

00:21:54.120 --> 00:21:56.540
So OpenGL is an industry standard.

00:21:56.540 --> 00:22:00.340
Apple works with companies like NVIDIA,
ATI,

00:22:00.340 --> 00:22:05.780
and Intel to continue to further OpenGL,
make it better for developers,

00:22:05.780 --> 00:22:09.230
easier to leverage functionality,
more efficient, but also to expose new

00:22:09.320 --> 00:22:10.680
hardware functionality.

00:22:10.940 --> 00:22:12.940
We make it such that as
new hardware comes out,

00:22:12.940 --> 00:22:15.120
we work with the standards
body to get that exposed

00:22:15.120 --> 00:22:16.690
functionality in the standard.

00:22:18.530 --> 00:22:22.820
New in Leopard is OpenGL 2.1,
and that includes GLSL 1.2,

00:22:22.820 --> 00:22:26.200
the high-level shading language.

00:22:26.200 --> 00:22:29.880
And like many of our other technologies,
we've spent the time to multithread it

00:22:29.890 --> 00:22:32.750
to make it efficient on your system,
optimized so that it runs

00:22:32.750 --> 00:22:34.320
at maximum performance.

00:22:35.360 --> 00:22:38.430
We've also built a 64-bit version,
so you can integrate this

00:22:38.430 --> 00:22:40.380
into your 64-bit applications.

00:22:40.380 --> 00:22:47.320
And part of the new shader language
is what we call Generation 4 shaders,

00:22:47.330 --> 00:22:51.050
and that includes geometry shaders.

00:22:51.120 --> 00:22:54.940
So now we have a new functional
programmable block on the pipeline,

00:22:55.030 --> 00:22:56.800
which is geometry shaders.

00:22:56.800 --> 00:22:58.980
And we've improved the tools.

00:22:58.980 --> 00:23:02.040
We've spent the time to
improve OpenGL Profiler and

00:23:02.040 --> 00:23:05.120
OpenGL Driver Monitor for debugging
and optimizing our applications.

00:23:05.360 --> 00:23:11.480
And we've improved Shader Builder
for building your shader effects.

00:23:14.920 --> 00:23:20.600
So some of you have probably
seen John Carmack's technology

00:23:20.600 --> 00:23:22.960
demonstration in the keynote.

00:23:22.990 --> 00:23:26.290
This represents his--

00:23:26.440 --> 00:23:28.400
Fifth-generation game engine.

00:23:28.500 --> 00:23:30.390
And we think this is a really
good example of what can be

00:23:30.390 --> 00:23:33.400
done with the power of OpenGL.

00:23:33.530 --> 00:23:36.990
We think this is a great
example of building an immersive

00:23:37.000 --> 00:23:39.030
3D cinematic application.

00:23:39.060 --> 00:23:44.100
And this is the kind of applications
that we hope are around the corner,

00:23:44.210 --> 00:23:48.830
that we're going to start seeing more and
more of on the platform as the graphics

00:23:48.830 --> 00:23:53.400
processor and the APIs to drive that
get more flexible and more powerful.

00:23:57.210 --> 00:23:58.660
So let's talk about QuickTime.

00:23:58.750 --> 00:24:02.020
QuickTime is another key technology
that we invest in at Apple.

00:24:02.020 --> 00:24:06.180
We've been investing
heavily in improving.

00:24:06.540 --> 00:24:08.960
An area we've been investing in is QtKit.

00:24:08.960 --> 00:24:15.480
QtKit is the Cocoa framework for
accessing QuickTime functionality,

00:24:15.480 --> 00:24:18.750
and it makes integrating
QuickTime functionality

00:24:18.750 --> 00:24:20.790
into your application easy.

00:24:21.750 --> 00:24:23.880
It also supports core animation.

00:24:23.940 --> 00:24:25.650
Like I had mentioned before,
you can embed a

00:24:25.650 --> 00:24:29.940
QuickTime movie onto a layer,
allowing you to perform animations.

00:24:29.940 --> 00:24:32.940
And we've added some new
API in QtKit for Leopard,

00:24:33.080 --> 00:24:35.760
and that is it supports device capture.

00:24:35.760 --> 00:24:41.390
You can capture video from iSights
and many USB and FireWire cameras.

00:24:41.400 --> 00:24:44.160
And it also supports 64-bit.

00:24:44.160 --> 00:24:48.240
This is the only way to
get QuickTime support

00:24:48.320 --> 00:24:51.400
in a 64-bit application.

00:24:56.550 --> 00:24:58.650
So let's look at a demo.

00:24:58.660 --> 00:25:01.240
And to do that,
I'm going to invite Geoff Staahl,

00:25:01.260 --> 00:25:04.000
the 3D graphics engineering manager,
up on the stage.

00:25:04.030 --> 00:25:07.750
And we're going to look at
a demo of World of Warcraft.

00:25:07.790 --> 00:25:12.220
And this is an interesting demo
because it combines two technologies,

00:25:12.220 --> 00:25:16.360
OpenGL and QuickTime together to bring
new capabilities to an application,

00:25:16.360 --> 00:25:17.680
new user functionality.

00:25:17.710 --> 00:25:20.800
And we thought it would be interesting to
look at this and see how that was done.

00:25:20.940 --> 00:25:22.680
So with that,
I'm going to hand it over to Geoff.

00:25:22.720 --> 00:25:24.330
GEOFF STALL: Thanks, John.

00:25:28.510 --> 00:25:30.420
We can go ahead and switch
to the demo machine.

00:25:30.420 --> 00:25:33.530
And what we're going to show here is
a little bit different than last year.

00:25:33.540 --> 00:25:35.980
Last year,
we showed how Blizzard has taken

00:25:35.980 --> 00:25:39.260
advantage of multi-threaded
OpenGL to greatly enhance the

00:25:39.260 --> 00:25:41.510
performance of their application.

00:25:41.510 --> 00:25:44.170
In this case,
we're going to show how Blizzard has

00:25:44.480 --> 00:25:47.410
taken a synergy of some of the
technologies we have here to

00:25:47.410 --> 00:25:51.230
greatly enhance the user experience,
allowing players to create great

00:25:51.440 --> 00:25:53.580
machinima productions in-game.

00:25:53.900 --> 00:26:00.250
What we're demonstrating is a new update
coming very shortly from Blizzard for

00:26:00.250 --> 00:26:04.140
Mac OS X that will allow in-game movie
capture and compression on the fly.

00:26:04.140 --> 00:26:07.080
So let's jump right in and show
you what you're going to have.

00:26:10.480 --> 00:26:12.680
So if we look under Mac Options,
now we have the ability to

00:26:12.770 --> 00:26:14.180
control movie recording.

00:26:14.220 --> 00:26:17.740
We're going to be recording
for the demo at 1024x768,

00:26:17.860 --> 00:26:20.360
30 frames per second,
and using an H.264 codec

00:26:20.460 --> 00:26:22.490
to compress on the fly.

00:26:24.990 --> 00:26:26.530
So as we run around,
one of the keys here is to

00:26:26.640 --> 00:26:30.780
actually integrate this into your
player experience so it doesn't

00:26:30.780 --> 00:26:33.070
really affect your gameplay.

00:26:33.190 --> 00:26:35.960
So I've just enabled the video capture.

00:26:35.960 --> 00:26:38.610
And if you notice,
the gameplay is still extremely fluid.

00:26:38.650 --> 00:26:44.910
Using the power of the GPU and
the multicore on this system,

00:26:45.310 --> 00:26:50.350
Blizzard has been able to put the video
capture in and the on-the-fly compression

00:26:50.480 --> 00:26:53.040
without detriment to your gameplay.

00:26:53.160 --> 00:26:56.070
So once you finish your adventure,
you can head back to the

00:26:56.070 --> 00:26:57.380
campfire to tell tall tales.

00:26:57.380 --> 00:27:00.440
And you can show who really
was the hero for that day.

00:27:00.450 --> 00:27:03.330
