00:31:33.390 --> 00:31:35.340
the stage for the web section.

00:31:35.340 --> 00:31:39.810
Mac OS X is a layered architecture,
and that's really stood us well over

00:31:39.810 --> 00:31:44.890
the test of time with the applications
and frameworks on top of graphics and,

00:31:44.890 --> 00:31:46.740
of course, the OS stack.

00:31:46.900 --> 00:31:48.830
So we've got a lot of stuff underneath.

00:31:48.830 --> 00:31:51.630
And if you think about it and
squint your eyes a little bit,

00:31:51.630 --> 00:31:53.720
the web is sort of
designed in the same way.

00:31:53.770 --> 00:31:55.780
There's websites,
which are kind of all the

00:31:56.190 --> 00:31:57.560
applications that run on the web.

00:31:57.840 --> 00:32:00.370
There's an HTML engine,
which provides the framework.

00:32:00.700 --> 00:32:04.290
There's a graphics layer underneath that
that supports the HTML engine for text

00:32:04.290 --> 00:32:07.930
and graphics and an operating system,
obviously, for the device that the

00:32:07.930 --> 00:32:09.790
browser is running on.

00:32:09.800 --> 00:32:14.480
And really, if you think about Apple's
implementation of the web,

00:32:14.480 --> 00:32:20.000
it really is all about... And one
thing we haven't mentioned so far is

00:32:20.000 --> 00:32:25.580
that actually the Quartz 2D API moves
with WebKit wherever WebKit goes.

00:32:25.620 --> 00:32:29.580
And so both iPhone and the
Windows implementation of

00:32:29.580 --> 00:32:31.840
WebKit rely on Quartz 2D.

00:32:31.840 --> 00:32:34.900
That's why we get such great
rendering fidelity across platform.

00:32:34.900 --> 00:32:37.760
And, of course, QuickTime,
the QuickTime plugin,

00:32:37.760 --> 00:32:41.340
plugs right into WebKit to provide
rich media services as well.

00:32:41.340 --> 00:32:43.560
So if you look at all the things
we're doing in this space,

00:32:43.570 --> 00:32:45.140
it's a pretty compelling platform.

00:32:45.140 --> 00:32:48.510
And to talk about that...
Across all of our products.

00:32:48.660 --> 00:32:49.370
Sorry, I missed that click.

00:32:49.580 --> 00:32:52.000
But to talk about this,
I'm going to invite Darren Adler

00:32:52.000 --> 00:32:54.650
up to the stage to talk
about Apple's web technology.

00:32:54.660 --> 00:32:55.650
Thank you.

00:33:03.390 --> 00:33:04.680
Thanks, Peter.

00:33:04.800 --> 00:33:08.900
So even though I'm the manager of
the team that developed Safari,

00:33:08.940 --> 00:33:10.940
I'm not really talking
just about Safari today.

00:33:11.200 --> 00:33:14.090
I want to take you on a quick
tour through the world of web

00:33:14.100 --> 00:33:16.220
applications and web technology.

00:33:16.220 --> 00:33:19.000
So first,
let's get a little bit of context.

00:33:19.110 --> 00:33:22.190
Here's a picture you've seen
earlier today a couple times,

00:33:22.320 --> 00:33:23.840
desktop as of 1984.

00:33:23.960 --> 00:33:29.980
The state of the art in terms of the look
with those snazzy rounded corners around

00:33:30.040 --> 00:33:32.970
the screen and in the user interface.

00:33:33.300 --> 00:33:35.020
The desktop has changed a lot.

00:33:35.150 --> 00:33:39.400
If you take a look at desktop today,
you see a lot more media,

00:33:39.400 --> 00:33:48.010
pictures everywhere, graphics,
and also a lot more richness.

00:33:48.440 --> 00:33:49.930
Well, the same kind of thing
has happened with the web.

00:33:50.030 --> 00:33:56.710
Here's the web as it looked in the Mosaic
browser at the dawn of the web in 1993.

00:33:56.760 --> 00:34:00.860
And websites are mostly
about text and links.

00:34:00.860 --> 00:34:03.260
There are plenty of pictures in them,
but occasionally.

00:34:03.260 --> 00:34:05.260
And the web has also changed.

00:34:05.260 --> 00:34:08.410
Alongside the desktop,
the web is also now full of media.

00:34:08.750 --> 00:34:11.640
Even a website like the
New York Times that's still basically

00:34:11.680 --> 00:34:17.500
about some information and some links
is full of elements that have media,

00:34:17.500 --> 00:34:19.290
have interaction.

00:34:19.300 --> 00:34:25.790
And this is what it looks like in
a modern browser like Safari 3.

00:34:26.170 --> 00:34:29.420
Both of these platforms,
the web technologies and

00:34:29.420 --> 00:34:33.600
the desktop platforms,
are obviously going to keep moving.

00:34:33.640 --> 00:34:37.520
And what happens is that capabilities
that were something you'd find

00:34:37.520 --> 00:34:40.760
only on the desktop in years
past become something that's

00:34:40.760 --> 00:34:42.930
achievable with web technology.

00:34:43.020 --> 00:34:45.490
I'll show you what I mean
by that in a moment.

00:34:46.080 --> 00:34:48.200
So what are some of the
distinguishing things about the web?

00:34:48.200 --> 00:34:50.600
Well,
we talked about the connectedness of the

00:34:50.950 --> 00:34:53.590
web and also the ubiquity of the web.

00:34:53.600 --> 00:34:55.870
If you take these four,
these are the top four

00:34:55.870 --> 00:34:58.950
browsers by market share,
Internet Explorer, Firefox, Safari,

00:34:58.950 --> 00:34:59.640
and Opera.

00:34:59.640 --> 00:35:02.950
If you take these four,
they cover a huge variety

00:35:02.950 --> 00:35:07.470
of devices and platforms,
everything from a kiosk in an airport,

00:35:07.470 --> 00:35:10.300
desktop computers, game consoles.

00:35:10.300 --> 00:35:13.200
You're going to be able to
get web content all over

00:35:13.210 --> 00:35:15.100
the place because of these.

00:35:15.100 --> 00:35:19.170
And what makes it work across all
these different browsers is the way

00:35:19.170 --> 00:35:22.540
that we cooperate and use standards.

00:35:23.180 --> 00:35:28.480
But even if you just think
about Safari 3 and WebKit,

00:35:28.510 --> 00:35:32.490
this is something that
you've got on Mac OS X,

00:35:32.490 --> 00:35:36.860
you've got on iPhone,
and also on Windows.

00:35:36.860 --> 00:35:40.310
So there's a lot of reach to web content.

00:35:41.340 --> 00:35:43.340
So what is a web application?

00:35:43.400 --> 00:35:47.800
Well, a lot of times you might
hear the term Web 2.0.

00:35:47.840 --> 00:35:50.390
And this was coined a few
years back by Tim O'Reilly,

00:35:50.400 --> 00:35:52.680
the famous technologist
and book publisher.

00:35:52.710 --> 00:35:57.490
And it's really about a new generation
of websites that are different

00:35:57.560 --> 00:36:00.200
from the websites on the early web.

00:36:00.210 --> 00:36:03.430
The kinds of things that we're
talking about when we talk about

00:36:03.430 --> 00:36:07.260
Web 2.0 are websites that involve
participation and also websites

00:36:07.260 --> 00:36:11.080
that start to have a feel that's
less about moving from page to page.

00:36:11.420 --> 00:36:14.380
And more like what you associate
with a desktop application.

00:36:14.600 --> 00:36:17.080
So now let's take a look at
some of these web applications

00:36:17.090 --> 00:36:18.460
to show what I'm talking about.

00:36:18.900 --> 00:36:21.470
Wikipedia is an interesting example.

00:36:21.700 --> 00:36:24.980
You take a look at this page full of
information like an encyclopedia page.

00:36:24.980 --> 00:36:28.250
And there's nothing there that
particularly makes it Web 2.0.

00:36:28.260 --> 00:36:31.000
But the key is the
interaction and participation.

00:36:31.000 --> 00:36:34.690
If you know more about
the Adelie Penguin and you

00:36:34.690 --> 00:36:41.280
want to add it to the site,
you edit it using this link.

00:36:41.280 --> 00:36:43.820
Wikipedia's editor.

00:36:44.130 --> 00:36:47.860
One of the seminal web applications
that had a lot of impact on

00:36:47.860 --> 00:36:55.340
what everybody thinks of being
possible on the web is Google Maps.

00:36:55.540 --> 00:37:00.140
Again, this is an application that when
you're using the map and manipulating

00:37:00.140 --> 00:37:02.930
it and searching for things,
you're not moving between web pages.

00:37:03.000 --> 00:37:06.440
You're using the kind of interaction
and clicks and gestures and user

00:37:06.440 --> 00:37:10.460
interface that's a little bit
more like a desktop application.

00:37:11.890 --> 00:37:16.180
37signals is a company that's
done a number of web applications,

00:37:16.320 --> 00:37:22.200
and this HiRise application is
an example of a contact manager.

00:37:22.290 --> 00:37:24.830
Now, these are applications for
keeping track of contacts,

00:37:24.940 --> 00:37:28.080
very popular for people in businesses
like sales who really need to

00:37:28.080 --> 00:37:29.760
keep track of who they talk to.

00:37:30.000 --> 00:37:33.240
And these are traditionally
desktop applications.

00:37:33.240 --> 00:37:36.430
Here's one built completely
with web technology.

00:37:36.730 --> 00:37:40.220
And then you get to some applications
that are really traditional desktop

00:37:40.760 --> 00:37:44.800
applications like word processors,
and Google Docs, formerly Rightly,

00:37:44.800 --> 00:37:47.630
is a complete word
processor implemented with

00:37:49.020 --> 00:37:50.410
Web Technology.

00:37:50.410 --> 00:37:53.370
So I'd like to show you
another web application.

00:37:53.420 --> 00:37:56.980
So let's go over here.

00:37:56.980 --> 00:37:58.980
One of my favorites.

00:38:06.750 --> 00:38:09.710
and this is the mail from .Mac.

00:38:09.710 --> 00:38:14.580
So if you're familiar,
if you haven't seen this before,

00:38:14.620 --> 00:38:16.880
you might not even realize that
we're looking at a web page.

00:38:16.940 --> 00:38:20.190
The main clues are the fact
that it's inside Safari and

00:38:20.190 --> 00:38:23.510
has the bars from Apple.com.

00:38:23.630 --> 00:38:30.270
But what's going on here is that
you have a mail application with

00:38:30.320 --> 00:38:33.630
a lot of the same qualities as
mail applications on the desktop.

00:38:33.680 --> 00:38:36.560
It looks a lot like the OS X Mail app.

00:38:36.700 --> 00:38:39.300
You click on a mail message
and see the message down below.

00:38:39.300 --> 00:38:43.600
These fancy ones look really great.

00:38:43.910 --> 00:38:47.110
And there's a lot of interaction
here that's exactly like what you

00:38:47.110 --> 00:38:48.690
would expect in a desktop app.

00:38:48.880 --> 00:38:52.160
For example,
if you choose a couple messages,

00:38:52.160 --> 00:38:56.720
you can delete them or
reply to any one message,

00:38:56.740 --> 00:38:58.460
mark them as unread,
all the same kind of commands

00:38:58.460 --> 00:39:01.390
you'd expect in the desktop.

00:39:01.630 --> 00:39:03.580
And also, the user interface is very
similar to the desktop.

00:39:03.580 --> 00:39:07.100
The user interface has elements
that you might not expect

00:39:07.100 --> 00:39:08.740
to find in the web at all.

00:39:08.780 --> 00:39:11.310
For example,
I can just take this message,

00:39:11.640 --> 00:39:13.780
drag it over and drop it into a folder.

00:39:13.780 --> 00:39:16.610
This is not what people think
about -- what most people think

00:39:16.650 --> 00:39:19.780
about when they think about web
pages and web user interface.

00:39:19.780 --> 00:39:22.770
So let's see.

00:39:22.780 --> 00:39:25.800
We can search for a word
like "team" and -- oh,

00:39:25.800 --> 00:39:27.780
that was the wrong word to search for.

00:39:27.780 --> 00:39:29.720
Let's not do that.

00:39:29.940 --> 00:39:33.500
Or I can search for somebody's
name in my address book.

00:39:33.500 --> 00:39:37.500
And just choose it here and
use it to address my mail.

00:39:37.500 --> 00:39:41.800
So really what you've got here is
something that has a lot of the

00:39:41.800 --> 00:39:45.920
properties of a desktop application,
even though it's implemented

00:39:45.920 --> 00:39:47.490
entirely with web technology.

00:39:50.500 --> 00:39:54.940
So let's go back to the slides.

00:39:55.030 --> 00:40:00.970
So even though this is a web application,
it's reminiscent of desktop apps.

00:40:01.100 --> 00:40:05.640
And it really is the kind of thing that
it looks like a desktop application,

00:40:05.640 --> 00:40:08.120
maybe not a desktop app of today,
but certainly a desktop

00:40:08.180 --> 00:40:10.320
app of a couple years ago.

00:40:10.370 --> 00:40:13.100
The techniques used to implement
this are a big part of a lot of

00:40:13.100 --> 00:40:15.130
the different Web 2.0 websites.

00:40:15.300 --> 00:40:18.770
And one interesting thing about
this is even though I was demoing

00:40:18.770 --> 00:40:21.820
that in the brand new Safari 3,
it works just fine

00:40:21.820 --> 00:40:23.720
with existing browsers.

00:40:23.720 --> 00:40:25.750
It doesn't require brand
new browser capabilities.

00:40:25.810 --> 00:40:28.030
It works great in Safari 2.

00:40:28.570 --> 00:40:33.050
So if you're putting
together a web application,

00:40:33.120 --> 00:40:35.470
there are a few things you want to do.

00:40:36.430 --> 00:40:38.660
One is that you want to make
sure that it works in any

00:40:38.660 --> 00:40:40.780
browser and degrades gracefully.

00:40:40.920 --> 00:40:43.580
And another is that just like
any software development,

00:40:43.860 --> 00:40:45.210
you'd like to reuse your code.

00:40:45.390 --> 00:40:50.890
You don't want to have every single
web application start from scratch.

00:40:51.290 --> 00:40:55.040
And to make that happen,
one of the most important things to

00:40:55.040 --> 00:40:57.440
do is to get a JavaScript library.

00:40:57.490 --> 00:41:02.320
JavaScript is the programming
language you use inside web pages

00:41:02.360 --> 00:41:05.720
alongside the markup languages,
HTML and CSS.

00:41:05.720 --> 00:41:14.230
And there are some really excellent
JavaScript libraries that have

00:41:14.230 --> 00:41:14.230
been a big part of the Web 2.0

00:41:14.210 --> 00:41:16.320
thing that's happening right now.

00:41:16.320 --> 00:41:19.540
Dojo, Scriptaculous,
which is built on prototype,

00:41:19.540 --> 00:41:22.450
are some of the richest and most popular.

00:41:22.540 --> 00:41:26.200
You can also build your
own JavaScript library.

00:41:26.200 --> 00:41:33.150
It's great language and it's
pretty easy to make reusable code.

00:41:33.150 --> 00:41:36.910
Here at Apple,
we do both of those things.

00:41:37.130 --> 00:41:40.060
And if you take a look at Apple websites,
you'll see all kinds of

00:41:40.060 --> 00:41:41.160
use of these libraries.

00:41:41.460 --> 00:41:44.160
One of the nice things about the
web is you can see the source code

00:41:44.180 --> 00:41:45.900
just with view source and all.

00:41:45.900 --> 00:41:48.880
And so see that we do
both of those things.

00:41:49.890 --> 00:41:53.760
Now, when the people build these sorts of
libraries and you build your site,

00:41:53.970 --> 00:41:56.760
there's really a rich set
of technologies to build on.

00:41:56.760 --> 00:41:59.590
A whole lot of stuff already
built into every browser,

00:41:59.590 --> 00:42:00.810
all the modern ones.

00:42:00.840 --> 00:42:05.560
And just to give you an idea of how
this relates to desktop technology,

00:42:05.610 --> 00:42:08.790
I picked out a few of the
fundamentals and listed the

00:42:08.850 --> 00:42:13.800
classes in AppKit or the techniques
in AppKit and the web techniques.

00:42:13.800 --> 00:42:16.150
And I'm not going to go
through all of these,

00:42:16.150 --> 00:42:20.240
but, you know, there's, you know,
if you want to do a table on the desktop,

00:42:20.470 --> 00:42:22.300
with AppKit, use NS Table View.

00:42:22.300 --> 00:42:24.120
There's the table element on the web.

00:42:24.120 --> 00:42:27.520
But let's talk for a moment
specifically about 2D graphics.

00:42:27.520 --> 00:42:33.240
So, because of the Canvas element,
which is an innovation originally

00:42:33.440 --> 00:42:38.180
created by Apple for Safari around
the time of Dashboard,

00:42:38.180 --> 00:42:40.900
which is now in most
of the modern browsers,

00:42:40.900 --> 00:42:44.590
you can do graphics operations.

00:42:44.920 --> 00:42:47.610
Pretty most of the graphics
operations that are in Quartz 2D

00:42:47.610 --> 00:42:49.510
are available to you within the web.

00:42:49.840 --> 00:42:52.580
So let's look at an example here.

00:42:52.630 --> 00:42:55.700
If you looked at
Apple applications recently,

00:42:55.700 --> 00:42:59.530
you may have noticed that to
create the illusion of a floor,

00:42:59.530 --> 00:43:01.460
we often reflect an image.

00:43:01.460 --> 00:43:04.360
In fact, I think of this as the rounded
corners of the 21st century.

00:43:04.360 --> 00:43:11.120
So to achieve this in a web page
is straightforward with Canvas.

00:43:11.130 --> 00:43:16.450
You simply have the image,
draw it twice with the proper settings

00:43:16.480 --> 00:43:18.580
to make the reflection look right.

00:43:19.850 --> 00:43:23.500
And so I just,
that's an example of achieving

00:43:23.500 --> 00:43:29.200
these things that you think of
as doing with desktop technology.

00:43:29.200 --> 00:43:31.880
Now another example is rich text editing.

00:43:31.880 --> 00:43:38.150
I list here one class, NSTextView,
as the Cocoa way to access rich text.

00:43:38.160 --> 00:43:41.260
And it is true that there's
only that one class you have

00:43:41.340 --> 00:43:44.740
to deal with to do the basics,
but there are really tons and

00:43:44.740 --> 00:43:48.400
tons of classes when it comes
to rich text editing in Cocoa.

00:43:48.400 --> 00:43:49.680
And the reason for that is
it's a really complex class.

00:43:49.700 --> 00:43:50.700
It's a complicated problem.

00:43:50.820 --> 00:43:54.300
It's one of the trickiest things
to do in an application framework.

00:43:54.340 --> 00:43:58.780
Now with Safari 3,
we have a full implementation of that

00:43:58.780 --> 00:44:04.860
rich text editing based on what is done
in other browsers and some web standards.

00:44:05.260 --> 00:44:09.890
Let me show you a little bit,
a little example of that.

00:44:13.960 --> 00:44:21.580
So this ties together the idea of
using a JavaScript library and also a

00:44:21.580 --> 00:44:23.910
little bit of an example of rich text.

00:44:24.050 --> 00:44:30.230
So imagine that this is a piece
of a web page that's editable.

00:44:30.590 --> 00:44:39.020
And because we want it to be
what you see is what you get,

00:44:39.020 --> 00:44:41.820
we don't want to put a lot of editing
controls on the page all the time.

00:44:41.820 --> 00:44:44.040
So instead,
what we do is make it so that once

00:44:44.070 --> 00:44:47.790
you make a selection in this text,
you get this attractive editing

00:44:47.790 --> 00:44:50.100
toolbar that appears around it.

00:44:50.100 --> 00:44:54.300
Now, any time you have
editable text in Safari,

00:44:54.520 --> 00:44:59.460
you have this whole menu full of
editing stuff that the browser

00:44:59.460 --> 00:45:01.980
supplies that's always there.

00:45:01.980 --> 00:45:03.100
So I'm going to use that.

00:45:03.130 --> 00:45:08.230
Just pull up the font panel,
make the text a little bigger,

00:45:08.300 --> 00:45:10.370
about 20 point.

00:45:10.560 --> 00:45:15.310
But in addition,
this toolbar gives you something

00:45:15.310 --> 00:45:19.910
that will appear in any browser that
lets you do these editing operations,

00:45:20.020 --> 00:45:24.620
bold some of the text,
make these three words italic,

00:45:24.620 --> 00:45:29.670
or even take a whole paragraph
and right justify it.

00:45:29.670 --> 00:45:35.500
And what I think is particularly cool
about this example is that it's a little

00:45:35.500 --> 00:45:40.130
bit of JavaScript to create this toolbar.

00:45:40.620 --> 00:45:43.540
And it's really beautiful.

00:45:43.540 --> 00:45:50.190
It's nice looking, nice experience,
and works with any browser.

00:45:52.140 --> 00:45:55.630
So that's an example of the kind
of building block that you might

00:45:55.630 --> 00:45:58.960
want to use when you're putting
together web applications.

00:45:58.960 --> 00:46:01.720
This particular one looks good.

00:46:01.890 --> 00:46:03.900
We're going to give you source code.

