And also, if you're doing that,
please check for the new WebKit version,

00:46:41.900 --> 00:46:44.970
not the new Safari version,
because we don't want to lock out other

00:46:44.970 --> 00:46:47.560
web browsers that are using WebKit.

00:46:49.290 --> 00:46:51.280
So I talked a little bit about
some of the things you use to

00:46:51.280 --> 00:46:53.650
put together a web application,
but there's another really

00:46:53.650 --> 00:46:56.220
interesting category,
what I'm referring to here

00:46:56.280 --> 00:46:57.940
as hybrid applications.

00:46:57.940 --> 00:47:02.000
Now, there are really these applications
that take advantage of web

00:47:02.000 --> 00:47:04.440
technologies and desktop technologies.

00:47:04.440 --> 00:47:09.300
Now, there's one category like World of
Warcraft that uses the Internet and

00:47:09.300 --> 00:47:13.770
networking on the back end and
desktop-type stuff on the front end.

00:47:14.030 --> 00:47:16.800
And that's really one type of hybrid app.

00:47:17.110 --> 00:47:19.620
But the kind I'm talking about is
one that wants to use other web

00:47:19.620 --> 00:47:21.390
technologies like HTML and JavaScript.

00:47:21.440 --> 00:47:24.550
And this is really
straightforward to do with Cocoa.

00:47:24.560 --> 00:47:27.280
You just create a web view,
which is an NSView subclass.

00:47:27.300 --> 00:47:30.990
There's all kinds of ways to use it,
rich text view if you're authoring HTML,

00:47:30.990 --> 00:47:32.470
to incorporate web pages.

00:47:32.480 --> 00:47:34.350
Let me just show you a
couple examples real quick.

00:47:37.730 --> 00:47:42.480
IChat in Leopard uses
WebView for its chat transcript.

00:47:42.480 --> 00:47:44.360
And what does that do for IChat?

00:47:44.360 --> 00:47:46.670
Well, one of the things it does
is you can have a bunch of

00:47:46.670 --> 00:47:49.660
different styles of transcript,
and you don't have to write separate

00:47:49.660 --> 00:47:52.530
code for those because the people
writing IChat didn't have to write

00:47:52.610 --> 00:47:55.530
separate code for those because
they can use CSS style sheets.

00:47:55.580 --> 00:48:01.780
So just by changing the style sheet,
I can make this chat instead

00:48:01.970 --> 00:48:04.710
look like this or like this.

00:48:04.760 --> 00:48:07.660
And all of that is done with
the style sheet language.

00:48:07.660 --> 00:48:11.190
You get that for free just
because you're using a WebView.

00:48:11.450 --> 00:48:19.340
Another example of sort of the premier
application using WebKit is Mail that

00:48:19.340 --> 00:48:22.470
uses WebKit for authoring all the mail.

00:48:22.880 --> 00:48:28.300
A great example of a third-party app
that's a true hybrid is NetNewsWire,

00:48:28.300 --> 00:48:32.640
which is an application to help
you read lots of news feeds.

00:48:32.810 --> 00:48:36.300
And here,
what WebView is really being used for is

00:48:36.300 --> 00:48:39.310
to be a mini web browser inside an app.

00:48:39.390 --> 00:48:44.110
And depending on the
type of app you have,

00:48:44.110 --> 00:48:44.110
you may need one of those.

00:48:44.110 --> 00:48:44.110
It's really easy to get one.

00:48:44.600 --> 00:48:46.710
Finally, I thought this was an
interesting example.

00:48:46.830 --> 00:48:52.260
There is a web chat
program called Campfire.

00:48:52.260 --> 00:48:53.940
And so it's just, it's a web application.

00:48:53.940 --> 00:48:54.730
It's on a web page.

00:48:54.730 --> 00:48:57.290
But they wanted to have
a desktop version of it.

00:48:57.350 --> 00:49:00.950
And so what they have here is this
application called Pyro is just

00:49:00.990 --> 00:49:03.330
really a single-purpose web browser.

00:49:03.380 --> 00:49:05.810
And I've seen a lot of
these cropping up recently,

00:49:05.810 --> 00:49:09.240
things that are called applications
that are really just a web browser

00:49:09.240 --> 00:49:12.380
that points to a particular site,
a real junction point between

00:49:12.380 --> 00:49:14.380
web technology and the desktop.

00:49:14.590 --> 00:49:19.550
So let me show you now one
of the most interesting

00:49:19.840 --> 00:49:21.140
and the rest of the world.

00:49:21.220 --> 00:49:26.160
This is actually something built
entirely with web technology.

00:49:26.410 --> 00:49:31.610
and others have been working on a new
web kit that is built into WebKit.

00:49:31.760 --> 00:49:35.070
It's not yet in the
versions that you get,

00:49:35.080 --> 00:49:38.880
say, on the Leopard DVD,
but it is going to be in

00:49:38.910 --> 00:49:41.360
nightly builds very soon.

