00:53:27.430 --> 00:53:28.000
too.

00:53:28.000 --> 00:53:34.480
So we think this is going to be really
popular for people doing web development,

00:53:34.480 --> 00:53:35.360
whether they're targeting
the desktop or iPhone.

00:53:45.840 --> 00:53:49.600
So this tool that will
help you build those apps,

00:53:49.600 --> 00:53:53.580
it was created entirely
with web technologies.

00:53:53.650 --> 00:53:56.240
And because of that,
it's going to work in

00:53:56.280 --> 00:53:59.790
any WebKit application,
and it also works in Safari.

00:53:59.800 --> 00:54:02.540
We didn't have to do a whole
new version just to make it

00:54:02.540 --> 00:54:04.660
work on Windows as well as OS X.

00:54:04.670 --> 00:54:09.280
And it's going to be available
soon in WebKit Nightly Builds.

00:54:11.240 --> 00:54:15.470
So Mac OS X is a really popular
platform for people who are

00:54:15.480 --> 00:54:16.880
developing content for the web.

00:54:16.880 --> 00:54:21.000
And I just wanted to dig a little bit
into the reason why it's so popular.

00:54:21.000 --> 00:54:22.630
This is something I've
heard for a long time.

00:54:22.640 --> 00:54:27.130
And I think one of the biggest reasons
is all the tools that are side by side.

00:54:27.140 --> 00:54:31.700
What's built into OS X are all
these unique server technologies,

00:54:31.700 --> 00:54:35.120
the very same server
technologies that many,

00:54:35.120 --> 00:54:37.560
if not most,
websites use on the back ends.

00:54:37.880 --> 00:54:42.330
And also there are these beloved
client-side tools that are really what

00:54:42.350 --> 00:54:44.930
people building websites love to use.

00:54:45.000 --> 00:54:46.540
And they're both there on OS X.

00:54:47.940 --> 00:54:50.960
So if you take a look at
all these built-in tools,

00:54:51.050 --> 00:54:53.730
I just picked a few here
to give you the idea.

00:54:54.060 --> 00:54:56.810
But these are a few of the things
that are built in that you can

00:54:56.810 --> 00:54:58.680
actually run on your OS X machine.

00:54:58.680 --> 00:55:01.830
And a lot of web developers I know sort
of run a small version of the site on the

00:55:01.830 --> 00:55:03.710
very same machine they're developing on.

00:55:03.710 --> 00:55:06.120
And you can do that without
having to add anything,

00:55:06.120 --> 00:55:08.070
because all this stuff comes built in.

00:55:08.820 --> 00:55:12.840
And then as far as client-side tools,
there are these crucial tools that

00:55:12.840 --> 00:55:16.550
you use both for content creation,
manipulating your images,

00:55:16.550 --> 00:55:19.090
editing your HTML,
and all that sort of thing.

00:55:19.090 --> 00:55:20.880
And both of these are available on OS X.

00:55:24.560 --> 00:55:25.850
But I think there's another reason.

00:55:25.940 --> 00:55:33.300
And I went and asked some web developers
why is it they like to develop on OS X.

00:55:33.300 --> 00:55:35.500
And this is what Jason Freed told me.

00:55:35.500 --> 00:55:39.300
Jason is the CEO and
founder of 37signals,

00:55:39.360 --> 00:55:43.350
the company that created and popularized
Ruby on Rails and also the application,

00:55:43.350 --> 00:55:44.860
a lot of web applications.

00:55:44.890 --> 00:55:48.950
And he said,
working on OS X reminds me that beauty,

00:55:48.950 --> 00:55:51.590
clarity, and workflow matter.

00:55:51.590 --> 00:55:54.480
That's a valuable reminder
when you're building a web app.

00:55:54.500 --> 00:55:55.850
about.

00:55:56.420 --> 00:56:00.030
So I think that there are some things
that go beyond just the concrete issues

00:56:00.060 --> 00:56:06.600
of exactly which tools are available
that affect people choosing OS X.

00:56:07.870 --> 00:56:13.460
So how is it that these web technologies
are put together and work across

00:56:13.460 --> 00:56:15.000
all of these different web browsers?

00:56:15.060 --> 00:56:17.940
The key is web standards.

00:56:18.070 --> 00:56:22.210
And I'm just going to say a
word or two about web standards.

00:56:22.390 --> 00:56:25.470
This is an open process that
involves all the different

00:56:25.480 --> 00:56:27.090
people who make web browsers.

00:56:27.190 --> 00:56:30.050
And in addition, lots of people are
interested in web technology.

00:56:30.190 --> 00:56:34.530
And the way the standards process works
helps prevent us from really diverging

00:56:34.760 --> 00:56:38.740
when we have these multiple browsers
all trying to work with the same web.

00:56:38.840 --> 00:56:43.980
And it also gives a way for innovations
to spread from one browser to another.

00:56:44.050 --> 00:56:46.730
The process is managed by
standards organizations.

00:56:46.740 --> 00:56:49.980
And two of the most important
standards organizations are the W3C.

00:56:49.980 --> 00:56:54.000
This is the original organization
that does the HTML standard and

00:56:54.110 --> 00:56:56.410
all sorts of vital web standards.

00:56:56.690 --> 00:56:59.260
And also, more recently,
there was a group called the

00:56:59.260 --> 00:57:02.040
What Working Group formed
a little while back.

00:57:02.080 --> 00:57:05.620
It was formed by the browser vendors who,
at the time, were a little bit frustrated

00:57:05.620 --> 00:57:09.640
with not enough standards that
really were relevant to the

00:57:09.730 --> 00:57:12.000
future directions of browsers.

00:57:12.020 --> 00:57:16.000
There's a recent standard that's
being developed that's actually being

00:57:16.000 --> 00:57:17.440
worked on by both of these groups.

00:57:17.440 --> 00:57:20.550
It was started in the
What Working Group and now

00:57:20.590 --> 00:57:23.370
is being worked on in both
W3C and What Working Group.

00:57:23.540 --> 00:57:28.580
And its original name was different,
but it's now called HTML5.

00:57:28.710 --> 00:57:32.580
And this standard is going to be a really
big deal for the future of the web.

00:57:32.580 --> 00:57:35.650
One of the things that
HTML5 is doing is defining,

00:57:35.770 --> 00:57:39.010
previously undocumented and undefined
things about the web very clearly

00:57:39.010 --> 00:57:43.980
so that the browsers will all be
able to implement them the same way.

00:57:44.020 --> 00:57:46.480
So it's really going to
help for compatibility.

00:57:46.670 --> 00:57:51.860
A lot of the new features that really
would help pushing Web 2.0 even further--

00:57:51.880 --> 00:57:53.080
I don't know if I was more of a marketer.

00:57:53.080 --> 00:57:56.130
It might say Web 3.0 there.

00:57:56.240 --> 00:58:00.560
And also,
some relevant Apple points are it

00:58:00.560 --> 00:58:04.780
includes Apple's Canvas element,
which we created and was

00:58:04.780 --> 00:58:09.200
quickly implemented in some
of the other major browsers.

00:58:09.200 --> 00:58:12.930
Some recent news-- we contributed a
design for video and audio elements.

00:58:13.060 --> 00:58:17.560
We really want to bring media out of the
plug-in world into the browser world.

00:58:17.560 --> 00:58:21.780
And our proposal was very well received.

00:58:21.780 --> 00:58:25.600
And it was a great example of bringing
a lot of the expertise that our

00:58:25.660 --> 00:58:27.280
media experts here have at Apple.

00:58:27.280 --> 00:58:32.290
Last thing I want to say about
HTML5 is that this is one of the

00:58:32.290 --> 00:58:35.100
easiest standards to participate in.

00:58:35.200 --> 00:58:37.920
It's even more open than most.

00:58:38.230 --> 00:58:40.890
The mailing list where the
technical issues are discussed is

00:58:40.910 --> 00:58:42.160
something you can subscribe to.

00:58:42.300 --> 00:58:46.000
If you're interested,
go to the W3C website.

00:58:48.320 --> 00:58:50.860
So what's coming in web technology?

00:58:51.210 --> 00:58:52.900
Well,
there's going to be more innovation.

00:58:52.900 --> 00:58:55.860
For us at Apple,
this standards and this whole

00:58:55.860 --> 00:58:59.150
space of web is a place where
we want to do a lot more.

00:58:59.150 --> 00:59:02.960
And as you can see, we're really serious
about web technology,

00:59:02.960 --> 00:59:06.610
having just brought Safari to
new platforms with a bunch of new

00:59:06.620 --> 00:59:09.190
features and an open-source approach.

00:59:09.240 --> 00:59:13.070
And I think there are some
opportunities for developers here.

00:59:13.150 --> 00:59:18.130
And one of them is,
if you have an existing website,

00:59:18.130 --> 00:59:22.550
turn it into a richer Web 2.0 website.

00:59:22.660 --> 00:59:27.830
Or if you have an application,
think about what kind of web presence

00:59:27.870 --> 00:59:30.600
really makes sense for your app.

00:59:30.940 --> 00:59:33.290
With the web technologies,
there are a whole variety of

00:59:33.290 --> 00:59:35.860
different ways to kind of add
the web to your desktop app.

00:59:35.900 --> 00:59:42.320
And there's also this situation
where Web 2.0 has undergone

00:59:42.320 --> 00:59:45.340
this explosive growth,
and I don't think the development tools

00:59:45.340 --> 00:59:47.100
have really caught up to that yet.

00:59:47.100 --> 00:59:48.910
So I think while there's
some really exciting new ones

00:59:48.950 --> 00:59:50.770
that have come out recently,
I think there's room for

00:59:50.780 --> 00:59:51.810
web development tools.

00:59:51.820 --> 00:59:54.140
So for some of you,
that may be an opportunity as well.

